<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-585-653  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 585 653.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 12 1990 v24 n46 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>SPA set to raid business site. (Software Publishers Association)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fitzgerald, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Software Publishers Association says it plans to raid a majorcorporation suspected of software piracy and run a new advertisingcampaign emphasizing the fact that piracy is theft.andP;  SPA officialssay they have obtained a search-and-seizure order to confiscatestolen programs from the unnamed company, which has severalhundred microcomputers.andP;  It will unveil the new ad campaign, whichfeatures the slogan 'Don't Copy That Floppy,' at the 1990Comdex/Fall trade show.andP;  The SPA's usual practice is to send acease-and-desist letter to the president of a company, filinglawsuits only against large companies or particularly seriousoffenders.andP;  A raid on three campuses of the National BusinessAcademy in May 1990 confiscated 600 allegedly pirated copies ofsoftware worth $250,000.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software Publishers AssociationLegal IssuesSoftware PiracySoftware protectionAuditingAuditing of Computer SystemsAdvertising.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Audit trail. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>